 medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud was born in 1165, in Angus, Scotland, United Kingdom. She married Gilbride Ogilvie II before 1197, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters."},"et":{"1165–":"1165–Surnud","1162–Male":"1162–Surnud","1177–Male":"1177–Surnud","1197–Male":"1197–Surnud","1208–1301":"1208–1301","–Female":"Surnud","1199–1250":"1199–1250","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","1301":"1301","1199":"1199","1177":"1177","1165":"1165","before 1197":"enne 1197","1197":"1197","1250":"1250","1162":"1162","1208":"1208","abt. 1197":"umbes 1197","about 1197":"umbes 1197","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Pury Ogilvy, Forfarshire, Scotland":"Angus, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe","Pury Ogilvy, Forfarshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Angus, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","of Pury Ogilvy, Forfar, Sctl.":"Angus, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Ogilvy, Forfarshire, Scotland":"Forfarshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1165–":"1165–Kuollut","1162–Male":"1162–Kuollut","1177–Male":"1177–Kuollut","1197–Male":"1197–Kuollut","1208–1301":"1208–1301","–Female":"Kuollut","1199–1250":"1